{
  "title": "Medium and Symbiotic Mechanism",
  "story": [
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "33463697f3759529",
      "text": "\"*Power* means any chance to assert one's own will within a social relationship even against opposition, no matter what this chance is based on,\" according to Max Weber (1985, 28) in *Wirtschaft und Gesellschaft* (Economy and Society). However, Weber's concept of power seems peculiarly amorphous because it can be applied everywhere and at any time. It lacks contour, an empirically relevant limitation of its possible applications, in order to be sociologically useful."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "7817f1f2169ead7a",
      "text": "If one turns to Luhmann's concept of power against this background, one recognizes the gain in conceptual precision, because Luhmann provides an exact definition of the situation within which power is applied. According to Luhmann, power is a social technology that is only used when a situation offers more than one possibility for action. Due to this possibility of choice, the principle of double contingency comes into play, which has a specific coordination problem as its object. For, assuming for simplicity only two persons, Alter and Ego, the question arises: How does Ego succeed in inducing Alter to act in a certain way, when Alter could just as well act differently? Such a situation requires power so that Ego's intention becomes Alter's binding decision and action specification. Luhmann calls this kind of technology, through which the action specification of one person (co-)conditions the behavior of another, symbolically generalized communication medium."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "748b2d4e62dd8936",
      "text": "Symbolically generalized communication media such as power, money, truth or love represent an evolutionary achievement (SA2, 170-192). The prerequisite is a certain scope of variation in possibilities of action, so that it is possible to react with rejection to certain specifications of action in favor of alternatives. If such alternatives do not exist, there is no need for power because rejection is highly unlikely. In this respect, the formation of the medium of power only occurs when, within a society, possibilities of rejecting prescriptions for action become apparent due to the increase in possibilities of also being able to act differently (M; Luhmann 2012). \"A need for power develops only when actions are communicated as decisions, that is, as selections that could also turn out differently; and when they refer to actions of another to which the same applies\" (PolG, 59)."
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "1513b812e9580127",
      "text": "This contingency leads to the fact that freedom becomes the indispensable reference value of power. Only where freedom prevails does power come into play. \"Power presupposes freedom\" (39). Therefore, it is crucial for the medium of power not to damage this condition of its possibility. For this reason, power is essentially threatening power: alter and ego each exchange arguments as to why it is advisable or not to adopt a course of action, and depending on who puts forward the better arguments, which by no means merely claim reasonableness for themselves, one wins this power game. The motives for giving in and giving in (*Nachgeben und Einlenken*) are often negative sanctions, which are threatened but are not used if possible. Luhmann therefore also speaks of the zero methodology of power, since the possibilities of punishment in the case of rejection of the action requirement, ultimately the use of force, are brought into play, but without this move actually being carried out."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "fb33d1ea0e554866",
      "text": "When one speaks of power, one cannot remain silent about violence. For violence, more precisely: physical violence, is the threatening means to which power most frequently refers in its application as ultima ratio. In this context, Luhmann (1974a) refers to violence as a symbiotic mechanism that is directed at the bodies of individuals and thus seeks to achieve direct control of the environment of the social system. Communication and the body are, in a sense, in a process of mutual influence (interpenetration). At the same time, because the political system alone claims the right to legitimately use violence, i.e., the monopoly on violence, violence functions as a central condition for the differentiation of the political system. Ultimately, however, the monopoly on the use of force is only a means to an end, since it is merely a way of enforcing the rules of action that is used as rarely as possible and therefore remains in the background (with binding force for all, who, if they fulfill certain characteristics – living within the boundaries of a certain territory – are attributed to an artificially constituted unit, namely the people). Rather, what is at stake is the monopoly of the possibility of decisions on how all who are considered citizens are to behave in a binding manner with regard to certain facts that are considered relevant to all. It is this concentration, indeed centralization, of power, insofar as it concerns the regulation of matters that concern everyone, that constitutes the political system."
    },
