        "type": "paragraph",
        "id": "7817f1f2169ead7a",
        "text": "If one turns to Luhmann's concept of power against this background, one recognizes the gain in conceptual precision, because Luhmann provides an exact definition of the situation within which power is applied. According to Luhmann, power is a social technology that is only used when a situation offers more than one possibility for action. Due to this possibility of choice, the principle of double contingency comes into play, which has a specific coordination problem as its object. For, assuming for simplicity only two persons, Alter and Ego, the question arises: How does Ego succeed in inducing Alter to act in a certain way, when Alter could just as well act differently? Such a situation requires power so that Ego's intention becomes Alter's binding decision and action specification. Luhmann calls this kind of technology, through which the action specification of one person (co-)conditions the behavior of another, symbolically generalized communication medium."
